                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d262">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M) Ecuador/169: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Scotten</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-06-17T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >June 17, 1943—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 10:22 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>528. Reference Department’s 416, May 29, 9 p.m.<note n="17" xml:id="d262fn17">Not
                        printed.</note> After July 1 the Ecuadoran Development Corporation will
                    commence acting as sole purchaser of cinchona bark. Authority is requested for
                        Fomento<note n="18" xml:id="d262fn18">Corporación Ecuatoriana de
                        Fomento.</note> to purchase for its own account any bark of less than 2%
                    rejected by Defense Supplies,<note n="19" xml:id="d262fn19">United States
                        representatives were authorized to purchase, at 10 cents a pound, cinchona
                        having alkaloids of 2% or above.</note> such bark to be sold to Argentina or
                    other foreign buyer. This would make complete control effective. The agreement
                    provides for free sale of bark not purchased in behalf of Defense Supplies.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Scotten</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
